{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489854"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:33:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:33:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"763"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/763"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.01,0.18,0.02,0.58]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67790"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/763"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67790"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 45-year-old woman is admitted with a two day history of constant right upper quadrant pain. The pain is increasing in severity and worse when she breathes in. She has no other symptoms. On examination she looks unwell, with a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 38.2C. Her BMI is 38. On light palpation there is tenderness in the right upper quadrant, which is more evident on deep palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most appropriately describes the abdominal examination findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["She is Murphy\u0027s positive","She is Murphy\u0027s negative","Murphy\u0027s sign is present","Murphy\u0027s sign is absent","No attempt has been made to elicit Murphy\u0027s sign"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMurphy\u0027s sign is either \u003Cstrong\u003Epresent\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsent\u003C/strong\u003E - it is not \u0027positive\u0027 or \u0027negative.\u0027 The concept of the manoeuvre that describes Murphy\u0027s sign is the attempted confirmation that a patient has a tender (inflamed) gallbladder, which is not palpable during standard abdominal examination of the patient with suspected acute cholecystitis. This is an unusual situation, as most patients with acute cholecystitis will have an easily detectable area of tenderness in the right upper quadrant. However, with the increasing prevalence of obesity, detection of abnormal abdominal physical signs can be difficult. Every now and again, a patient with an inflamed gallbladder will not have any localised tenderness and asking the patient to inhale (and depress the diaphragm) with the examination fingers held gently, but firmly immediately under the right costal margin, will cause the patient to catch their breath as the tender gallbladder touches the peritoneum being depressed by the examiner\u0027s hand - and then \u0027Murphy\u0027s sign is present.\u0027 ie the patient has been observed to hold their breath (on inspiration) when the inflamed gallbladder comes into contract with the peritoneum. This is not the exact physical manoeuvre described by Murphy, but does follow the principle he enunciated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe phrase \u0027\u003Cstrong\u003Enegative Murphy\u0027s\u003C/strong\u003E\u0027 is frequently used by those who do not understand the term and it has no meaning. Similarly, the phrase \u0027\u003Cstrong\u003EMurphy\u0027s positive\u003C/strong\u003E\u0027 is often used to describe right upper quadrant tenderness which is already evident when the patient is lying at rest. In the case described in this clinical stem, tenderness is already obvious when palpating the right upper quadrant and thus \u003Cstrong\u003Eno attempt has been made to elicit Murphy\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E. Such action would be redundant (and painful for the patient) as an area of localised tenderness has already been identified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is a tendency to try and move away from the use of eponyms in medical practice. In the case of peritoneal irritation and overlying tenderness in cases of suspected acute cholecystitis, greater clarity is achieved by saying either \u0027there is right upper quadrant tenderness\u0027 or \u0027there is no right upper quadrant tenderness.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Murphy\u0027s sign is now mis-used and the original description (of tenderness elicited by asking the patient to breath in whilst gently pushing under the right subcostal margin) is forgotten."],"references":["Jeans PL, Murphy\u0027s sign. MJA 2017; 206:116-17. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28208037/","Musana KA, Yale SH. Murphy\u0027s sign. Clin Med Res 2005;3:131-32. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16160065/","Perera E, Khan A, Sarraf KM, et al. Orthopaedic Eponyms: A Tool of the Past. Cureus 15(8): e43336. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37700939/","Woywodt A, Matteson E. Should eponyms be abandoned? BMJ 2007; 335:424-25. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17762033/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"763"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53255"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T00:42:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-27T08:50:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"763"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67790"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"